1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,339
Welcome, today, in this analysis, we dive into a real mystery of our

2
00:00:05,339 --> 00:00:06,339
society.

3
00:00:06,339 --> 00:00:12,099
Think about it for a second, why do some democracies seem to flourish, driven by huge citizen

4
00:00:12,099 --> 00:00:17,179
participation, while others struggle tremendously, even just to make basic

5
00:00:17,179 --> 00:00:18,179
institutions work?

6
00:00:18,179 --> 00:00:23,300
Well, let's dive into the data to discover the hidden dynamics that connect our most

7
00:00:23,300 --> 00:00:26,460
intimate relationships, family ones, to the entire public sphere.

8
00:00:26,859 --> 00:00:32,160
But ultimately, what really determines our democratic engagement? What drives an entire

9
00:00:32,160 --> 00:00:36,939
population to get up in the morning to go vote, to volunteer, to sign

10
00:00:36,939 --> 00:00:40,980
petitions, or simply to trust their own institutions?

11
00:00:40,980 --> 00:00:44,700
You might think it's just a matter of money, right?

12
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:46,620
Or maybe formal education.

13
00:00:46,620 --> 00:00:51,620
And yet, evidence suggests that the answer might lie much, much

14
00:00:51,620 --> 00:00:56,280
closer to us, literally inside our homes and in the traditions we

15
00:00:56,280 --> 00:00:58,800
absorb from the time we are children.

16
00:00:58,800 --> 00:01:04,799
Section 1, the mystery of civic participation, let's go see what it is about.

17
00:01:04,799 --> 00:01:08,799
Section 2, the theory of amoral familism.

18
00:01:08,799 --> 00:01:14,319
It all starts with an observation, I would dare say illuminating, made by an American researcher,

19
00:01:14,319 --> 00:01:19,240
Edward Banfield. Imagine being in a small village in southern Italy in the

20
00:01:19,240 --> 00:01:20,240
50s.

21
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:26,200
Banfield notices something very peculiar and coins this term, amoral familism.

22
00:01:26,200 --> 00:01:31,719
What is it, exactly? In practice, it is a social equilibrium where people blindly trust

23
00:01:31,719 --> 00:01:37,000
and care exclusively about their own immediate family—and so far, so good—but the

24
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:41,159
point is that they expect everyone else to do exactly the same.

25
00:01:41,159 --> 00:01:45,640
Consequently, and it is entirely rational from their point of view, they don't trust at all

26
00:01:45,640 --> 00:01:50,200
anyone outside the family circle. It's as if an invisible wall is created toward

27
00:01:50,200 --> 00:01:54,359
public affairs, because everything that is not family is viewed with deep

28
00:01:54,359 --> 00:01:55,359
suspicion.

29
00:01:55,519 --> 00:02:01,680
And the crazy thing is how all this is transmitted over time, almost like an intergenerational

30
00:02:01,680 --> 00:02:03,920
instruction manual.

31
00:02:03,920 --> 00:02:09,060
Let's look at the steps: first, children are taught absolute trust toward

32
00:02:09,060 --> 00:02:10,080
their family members.

33
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:15,719
Second, a strong distrust of strangers is instilled in parallel.

34
00:02:15,719 --> 00:02:21,039
Third, and this is a crucial indicator, obedience is taught as a virtue far

35
00:02:21,039 --> 00:02:26,199
superior to personal initiative; that is, those who stay in their place are rewarded, creating

36
00:02:26,199 --> 00:02:28,959
a real resistance to change.

37
00:02:28,959 --> 00:02:34,120
Fourth and final step, the result of this chain is very low civic participation,

38
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:39,159
which unfortunately persists relentlessly across generations.

39
00:02:39,159 --> 00:02:43,039
Section 3, global data, family versus politics.

40
00:02:43,039 --> 00:02:48,359
Now let's broaden our view, leave the single village behind, and look at the data from the

41
00:02:48,360 --> 00:02:52,680
World Values Survey, an incredibly rigorous global survey.

42
00:02:52,680 --> 00:02:56,040
And here, a crazy contrast emerges between different cultures.

43
00:02:56,040 --> 00:02:58,280
On one hand, we have Northern Europe.

44
00:02:58,280 --> 00:03:03,200
Family ties are weaker, but we find very high social capital, a lot of

45
00:03:03,200 --> 00:03:06,400
trust in strangers, and huge civic participation.

46
00:03:06,400 --> 00:03:11,120
On the other hand, we find Southern Europe, but also Latin America and various areas of Asia

47
00:03:11,120 --> 00:03:12,120
and Africa.

48
00:03:12,120 --> 00:03:17,000
Here, family is everything, bonds are incredibly strong and cohesive, yet civic engagement and

49
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:19,000
trust in institutions collapse.

50
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,759
But wait, we must be very clear on this point: we are not saying that one

51
00:03:23,759 --> 00:03:28,960
culture is good and the other bad, we are simply and objectively observing

52
00:03:28,960 --> 00:03:31,240
how different societies choose to organize themselves.

53
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:37,240
And the numbers from this study confirm an inverse relationship that is rock-solid: the more

54
00:03:37,240 --> 00:03:40,199
weight you give to family, the less you care about politics.

55
00:03:40,199 --> 00:03:44,960
And the thing that literally drives me crazy is that this rule holds even if we remove

56
00:03:44,960 --> 00:03:48,400
elements like income or level of education from the equation.

57
00:03:48,400 --> 00:03:53,080
To give you a concrete perspective, imagine taking a person with very loose family ties

58
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:55,879
and one with very strong ties.

59
00:03:55,879 --> 00:04:00,640
Well, the increase in political disinterest between these two extremes is comparable to the impact

60
00:04:00,640 --> 00:04:05,960
you would have if we took a college graduate and suddenly gave them only an elementary

61
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:06,960
education.

62
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:09,080
The effect of culture is simply devastating.

63
00:04:09,080 --> 00:04:13,719
And mind you, we are not just talking about chatting at a bar.

64
00:04:13,719 --> 00:04:18,759
The study measured the willingness to take actual action: things like signing

65
00:04:18,759 --> 00:04:23,920
petitions, boycotting products, taking to the streets in authorized demonstrations, all the way

66
00:04:23,920 --> 00:04:29,240
to wildcat strikes and occupying buildings—in short, the whole complete package

67
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:30,240
of activism.

68
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:35,800
And the data is clear: those with ironclad family ties are systematically less likely

69
00:04:35,800 --> 00:04:41,300
to do even just one of these things, less volunteering, fewer demonstrations, as if

70
00:04:41,300 --> 00:04:46,060
all the energy were absorbed to the very last drop by the home environment.

71
00:04:46,060 --> 00:04:47,060
Section 4.

72
00:04:47,060 --> 00:04:48,060
The ultimate proof.

73
00:04:48,060 --> 00:04:49,060
Immigrants.

74
00:04:49,060 --> 00:04:55,300
Okay, at this point you might legitimately tell me, "Sorry, but maybe it's the fault of local

75
00:04:55,300 --> 00:05:00,300
institutions that suck and discourage people," a very fair objection.

76
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:03,860
And this is where the study's true stroke of genius comes in.

77
00:05:03,860 --> 00:05:08,980
To separate culture from the environment, they used the European Social Survey to analyze

78
00:05:08,980 --> 00:05:11,340
second-generation immigrants.

79
00:05:11,340 --> 00:05:15,819
We are talking about people born and raised, who go to school and work under the exact same

80
00:05:15,819 --> 00:05:18,259
laws and institutions as local citizens.

81
00:05:18,259 --> 00:05:23,220
So the reasoning is simple: if their way of relating to politics is different

82
00:05:23,220 --> 00:05:28,060
from the local average and instead resembles that of their parents' country of origin, well,

83
00:05:28,060 --> 00:05:29,060
bingo.

84
00:05:29,060 --> 00:05:33,300
It means we are looking at a purely cultural trait, transmitted within the family,

85
00:05:33,300 --> 00:05:35,460
and not a problem with local institutions.

86
00:05:35,460 --> 00:05:36,460
32.

87
00:05:36,579 --> 00:05:38,459
Yes, you heard that right.

88
00:05:38,459 --> 00:05:41,939
32 is the number of different destination countries analyzed.

89
00:05:41,939 --> 00:05:45,500
They didn't just look at those who immigrate to the United States, as is often done.

90
00:05:45,500 --> 00:05:50,259
With such a wealth of data spread across 32 nations, any single doubt is eliminated

91
00:05:50,259 --> 00:05:54,299
that the results might be distorted by the rules of a single country.

92
00:05:54,299 --> 00:05:56,979
It's an analysis of impressive robustness.

93
00:05:56,979 --> 00:06:00,819
And looking at this data, the picture comes together perfectly.

94
00:06:00,819 --> 00:06:05,339
Children of those who come from countries with strong family ties, even if they live in a

95
00:06:05,340 --> 00:06:09,420
completely new environment, maintain very specific behaviors.

96
00:06:09,420 --> 00:06:14,420
They watch the news less, read less about politics, are less interested in public affairs,

97
00:06:14,420 --> 00:06:16,660
and trust strangers much less.

98
00:06:16,660 --> 00:06:20,640
It really seems that strong family ties and generalized trust play a

99
00:06:20,640 --> 00:06:24,740
zero-sum game: if you pour almost your entire reserve of trust into the

100
00:06:24,740 --> 00:06:29,500
family unit, there is really very little left, if not none, to spend in the outside

101
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:30,500
world.

102
00:06:30,500 --> 00:06:38,180
Section 5, strong ties, a final balance, having reached this point, it is absolutely vital

103
00:06:38,180 --> 00:06:39,660
to make a clarification.

104
00:06:39,660 --> 00:06:44,899
Having extremely strong family ties is not a disease to be cured, it is simply a

105
00:06:44,899 --> 00:06:49,180
different equilibrium, with its immense pros and cons.

106
00:06:49,180 --> 00:06:53,459
Family-focused societies offer an incredible emotional and economic safety

107
00:06:53,459 --> 00:06:58,459
net; those who live there report high levels of personal satisfaction and a very high domestic

108
00:06:58,460 --> 00:07:01,500
production, understood as mutual care.

109
00:07:01,500 --> 00:07:05,100
The price to pay, however, is less trust in institutions.

110
00:07:05,100 --> 00:07:09,780
Conversely, societies with weak ties make the public democratic machine work great

111
00:07:09,780 --> 00:07:15,020
and trust their neighbor, but they must give up this warm and totalizing haven

112
00:07:15,020 --> 00:07:16,460
of the large united family.

113
00:07:16,460 --> 00:07:22,140
And all this explainer leaves us with a giant question for our future: since,

114
00:07:22,140 --> 00:07:27,100
as we have just seen, family values change very slowly, what

115
00:07:27,100 --> 00:07:28,500
will happen now?

116
00:07:28,500 --> 00:07:33,780
Will globalization slowly make us all the same, smoothing out these differences,

117
00:07:33,780 --> 00:07:38,040
or, on the contrary, will this increasingly fast-paced world trigger the instinct to

118
00:07:38,040 --> 00:07:42,460
cling even more to these local family roots to protect them?

119
00:07:42,460 --> 00:07:44,580
It's a fascinating dynamic, isn't it?

120
00:07:44,580 --> 00:07:49,260
It makes us realize how, in the end, that simple table around which we dine in the evening continues,

121
00:07:49,260 --> 00:07:53,660
in the silence of our homes, to shape the very destiny of our democracies.